Business Task

Task Summary

Our company wants to unlock new growth opportunities and would like us to analyse smart device fitness data to gain insight into how consumers are using their non-Bellabeat smart devices. They would then like us to use these insights to provide recommendations for the marketing strategy for our Time product - the wellness watch which tracks user activity, sleep, and stress.

Stakeholders

  • Urka Sren: Bellabeats cofounder and Chief Creative Officer
  • Sando Mur: Mathematician and Bellabeats cofounder
  • Bellabeat marketing analytics team: A team of data analysts responsible for collecting, analyzing, and reporting data

Data Preparation

Source

Our dataset has been sourced from kaggle. This data was generated by 30 respondents to a distributed survey via Amazon Mechanical Turk between 03/12/2016 - 05/12/2016. The metadata confirms this data has no copyright and has the CC0 licence.

There are 18 csv files contained in this dataset, however, there is no metadata to describe how the data is organised for each file.

Data Organisation

The data was imported into BigQuery to examine the organisation of the data. The schema was used to find out what columns each file contained. In addition, the tables were previewed to further understand the data and queries were ran to find out the number of rows and number of unique IDs:

SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM table_name;

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT Id)
FROM table_name;

Using this information, I created the following table to summarise the contents of each dataframe:

This document from Fitabase provides descriptions of the data.

Limitations

Limitations to this data include:

  • 5.5 years old data - May not be relevant due to changing fitness trends
  • Data limited to one month - Not enough data to identify trends such as seasonal trends
  • Small sample size of 33 participants with some files containing data for even less participants - May not be enough participants to represent the whole population
  • Lack of demographic information - Sample may not be representative of the demographic Bellabeat is targeting
  • Third party data - Unsure on the reliability of this data

Cleaning

Column names

To keep the column names consistent across the dataframes, the columns in the minuteSleep_merged.csv file were renamed to keep in line with the PascalCase naming convention used for field names in the rest of the dataframes:

minute_sleep <- rename_with(minute_sleep, str_to_title)

After renaming the column names, the dataframe was examined to verify that the names had been correctly changed:

colnames(minute_sleep)
## [1] "Id"    "Date"  "Value" "Logid"

In addition, to prevent confusion, columns named LightActiveDistance were renamed to LightlyActiveDistance and columns named FairlyActiveMinutes were renamed to ModeratelyActiveMinutes as the description for this field is Total minutes spent in moderate activity.

daily_activity <- rename(daily_activity, c(ModeratelyActiveMinutes = FairlyActiveMinutes, LightlyActiveDistance=LightActiveDistance))
daily_intensities <- rename(daily_intensities, c(ModeratelyActiveMinutes = FairlyActiveMinutes, LightlyActiveDistance=LightActiveDistance))

Data Aggregation

The following code was used to calculate the total number of minutes recorded each day for each Id:

daily_total_minutes <- daily_activity %>%
  group_by(Id, ActivityDate) %>%
  summarise(TotalMinutes = sum(VeryActiveMinutes, ModeratelyActiveMinutes, LightlyActiveMinutes, SedentaryMinutes))

The following code was used to calculate the number of days of recorded data for each Id:

days_recorded <- daily_activity %>%
  count(Id, sort=TRUE) %>%
  setNames(c("Id", "DaysRecorded"))

The following code was used to calculate the number of days with zero steps recorded for each Id:

days_inactive <- daily_activity %>%
  group_by(Id) %>%
  summarise(DaysInactive = sum(TotalSteps = 0))

The following code was used to calculated the average daily steps for each user:

activity_level <- daily_activity %>%
  group_by(Id) %>%
  summarise(AverageSteps = mean(TotalSteps))

Merging Dataframes

Dataframes representing same time intervals were merged together.

daily_data <- daily_activity %>%
  merge(daily_total_minutes, by=c('Id', 'ActivityDate')) %>%
  left_join(daily_sleep, by=c('Id'='Id', 'ActivityDate'='SleepDay'))

hourly_data <- hourly_calories %>%
  merge(hourly_intensities, by=c('Id', 'ActivityHour')) %>%
  merge(hourly_steps, by=c('Id', 'ActivityHour'))

The aggregated days_recorded and days_inactive data were merged to create a summary dataframe.

activity_summary <- days_recorded %>%
  merge(days_inactive, by='Id') %>%
  merge(activity_level, by='Id')

Grouping Users

The number of days each user was active for was calculated from the activity summary dataframe:

activity_summary$DaysActive <- activity_summary$DaysRecorded - activity_summary$DaysInactive

The users were then placed into usage groups based on the number of days they used their device:

activity_summary <- activity_summary %>%
  mutate(Usage = case_when(
    DaysActive >= 0 & DaysActive < 11 ~ "Low",
    DaysActive >= 11 & DaysActive < 21 ~ "Moderate", 
    DaysActive >= 21 & DaysActive < 31 ~ "High"))

The users were also placed into activity level groups based on their average steps per day. The boundaries for each group were determined by this article:

activity_summary <- activity_summary %>%
  mutate(ActivityLevel = case_when(
    AverageSteps < 2500 ~ "Basal Activity",
    AverageSteps >= 2500 & AverageSteps < 5000 ~ "Limited Activity", 
    AverageSteps >= 5000 & AverageSteps < 7500 ~ "Low Activity",
    AverageSteps >= 7500 & AverageSteps < 10000 ~ "Somewhat Active",
    AverageSteps >= 10000 & AverageSteps < 12500 ~ "Active",
    AverageSteps >= 12500 ~ "Highly Active",
    ))

These groups were then added to the daily_data and hourly_data dataframes:

daily_data <- daily_data %>%
  merge(select(activity_summary, Id, Usage, ActivityLevel), by='Id')

hourly_data <- hourly_data %>%
  merge(select(activity_summary, Id, Usage, ActivityLevel), by='Id')

Data Analysis

Tableau was used to analyse and visualise the data.

write.csv(daily_data, 'C:\\Users\\Jason\\Desktop\\dailyData.csv', row.names = FALSE)

Usage Groups

The following dashboard shows the distribution of users between usage groups, as well as the distribution of activity levels within those usage groups:

  • From the bar chart we can see that the majority are using their devices regularly, with over 75% of users in the high usage group.

  • From the pie charts we can see that users that use their devices more regularly tend to also be more active.

  • Between the moderate and high usage groups, there is a similar percentage of users that have a limited or low level of activity. However, the moderate usage group has nearly 43% of users that have a basal level of activity, whereas the high usage group has none. This proportion of users is instead, spread across the somewhat active, active and highly active groups.

Average Steps per Day

The following dashboard compares the average total steps for each day across all users, as well as the average total steps per day for each activity level:

  • The average daily steps of the user increases as the activity level of the user increases, this is because the activity level is determined by this variable.

  • Tuesday and Saturday are the most active days being around 500 steps above the daily average, as well as being above the daily average in 4/6 and 5/6 groups respectively.

  • Sunday is the least active day being around 700 steps below the daily average, as well as being below the daily average in 5 groups.

Average Steps per Hour

The following dashboard shows the average steps per hour of the day across all users, as well as the average steps per hour for each activity level:

  • There are peaks at 12:00-14:00 and 18:00-19:00, with a smaller peak at 10:00. This could be that for people who work, these times are when they are able to be more active, i.e, when they have breaks or have finished work.

  • The three highest activity levels have three peaks whereas the three lowest activity levels have only two.

  • The high activity levels has two large spikes of activity at 14:00 and 19:00 with a smaller spike at 21:00-22:00. The two main peaks are at expected times but the morning spike is not present and the spike at 21:00-22:00 is not seen in any of the other activity levels.

Daily Steps per Usage Group

The following visualisation shows the distribution of total daily steps for each usage group:

  • As usage increases, so does the range of values for total daily steps.

  • I would expect the median total daily steps to increase as usage increases, however, the median for the moderate group is lower than the median for the low usage group. This is could be due to a lack of data for the low usage group.

Daily Steps per Activity Level

The following visualisation shows the distribution of total daily steps for each activity level:

  • As explained before, the total daily steps increases as activity levels increase.

  • The trend between the groups is that the range of total daily steps increases as the activity level increases. The active group doesnt follow this trend however, the range decreases and the lower whisker is at 5600 steps, this suggests that this group has a more consistent level of activity without resting.

  • The basal activity and highly active groups are both positively skewed which suggests that they spend more days where they are not as active than days where they are active.

Average Minutes Slept per Activity Level

The following visualisation shows the average minutes slept for each activity level:

  • The two most active groups slept the least out of the six groups. This could be because more intense activity can benefit sleep quality as suggested by this study.

Total Minutes Slept per Day

The following visualisation shows the distribution of total minutes slept for each day:

  • Compared to the weekend, there is a narrower range for time slept on weekdays. The ranges for time slept from Monday-Friday are between 305-391 minutes, this is likely due to people being in a routine for work.

  • The ranges for total minutes slept on Saturday and Sunday are wider, with the ranges being 598 minutes and 563 minutes respectively. This is likely to be due to people having less commitments on the weekend which allows them more flexibility with how long they sleep for.

Time in Bed Vs Time Asleep

The following visualisation shows the relationship between total time in bed and total time asleep:

  • There is a positive linear relationship between total time in bed and total minutes slept.

  • The points highlighted in red are from two users who may have difficulties getting to sleep as they spend a lot more time in bed than users who have slept for the same amount of time.

Conclusion

Main Takeaways

  • Activity levels generally increase with usage.
  • Tuesday and Saturday are the most active days and Sunday is the least active day.
  • More active users are active three times a day whereas less active users are active twice a day or less.
  • Peak times for activity are generally at 10:00, 12:00-14:00 and 18:00-19:00. The exception to this is at 21:00-22:00 which is a peak time for the highly active users.
  • The range for total daily steps generally increases with usage levels and also activity levels.
  • The most active users sleep less than others.
  • Sleeping patterns are less consistent on weekends.
  • There is a positive linear relationship between total time in bed and total minutes slept.

Recommendations

Future Analyses

  • Include user demographics in the analysis
  • Use data from current Bellabeat users so that the data is more relevant to our target population
  • Increase sample size so that data is more precise and we can be more confident with regards to our findings
  • Better group users through unsupervised machine learning to provide more accurate insights

Marketing Strategy

  • Advertise Bellabeat to women interested in fitness. The combination of our app and devices can help users stay active and reach fitness goals through notifications and rewards systems. We can also analyse their activity patterns and provide recommendations.

  • Advertise Bellabeat to women who search for sleep aids or are awake late at night. The combination of our app and devices can use their sleep data to identify people who have irregular sleeping patterns or have difficulty getting to sleep. Using this information we can help them to get into a routine, improve their activity and therefore sleep quality, and provide advice on good sleep hygiene.
